  "prompt": "Is \"why you went there?\" proper grammar?",
  "response": "The phrase **\"Why you went there?\"** is not considered proper grammar in standard English because it is missing an auxiliary verb (also called a helping verb). A grammatically correct version would include a helping verb, depending on the intended meaning:\n\n1. **Past Tense (Simple Question):**  \n   \"Why **did** you go there?\"  \n   (This is the most natural and common way to ask this question in past tense.)\n\n2. **Present Perfect Tense:**  \n   \"Why **have** you gone there?\"  \n   (This would be used to emphasize a connection to the present or a repeated action.)\n\n3. **Direct or Informal Speech:**  \n   In very casual or informal contexts, people might omit the auxiliary verb (e.g., \"Why you go there?\"), but this is not considered grammatically correct in formal writing or speech.\n\nSo, **\"Why did you go there?\"** is the proper and standard way to phrase this question.",
